      <text xml:space="preserve">{{wiktionary|Atlantic}}

The '''[[Atlantic Ocean]]''' is the second largest of the world's oceans.

'''Atlantic''' may also refer to:

==In geography==
* [[Atlantic, Nova Scotia]], Nova Scotia
* [[Atlantic, Iowa]], Iowa
* [[Atlantic, North Carolina]], an unincorporated community in eastern Carteret County situated along the Core Sound, located in what was known to early settlers of the area as Hunting Quarters
* [[Atlantic, Pennsylvania]]
* [[Atlantic, Virginia]]
* [[Atlantic County, New Jersey]]
* [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]]

==In transportation==
* [[Atlantic (1921 automobile)]], an obsolete automobile company
* [[Atlantic (train)|''Atlantic'' (train)]], a named passenger train operated by Canadian Pacific Railway and later VIA Rail
* [[Atlantic (locomotive)|''Atlantic'' (locomotive)]], an early steam-powered locomotive of the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad with a 0-4-0 wheel arrangement
* A [[4-4-2 (locomotive)|steam locomotive]] with a 4-4-2 wheel arrangement (UIC classification 2B1), &lt;!-- this is a different locomotive than above --&gt;
* [[RMS Atlantic]], a steamship that sank off Halifax, Nova Scotia in 1873
* [[Atlantic (yacht)|''Atlantic'' (yacht)]], a three-masted gaff-rigged schooner
* [[Atlantic Airways]], a Faroese airline company
* [[Virgin Atlantic]], a British airline company
* [[Breguet Atlantic]], a French aircraft

==In media==
* [[Atlantic (song)|&quot;Atlantic&quot; (song)]], a 2006 song by the British rock band Keane
* [[Atlantic (song)|&quot;Atlantic&quot; (song)]], a 2006 song by Northern Irish rock band Lafaro
* [[Atlantic (1929 film)|''Atlantic'' (1929 film)]], a black and white British film
* [[Atlantic Records]], a record company
* [[Atlantic FM]], a radio station serving Cornwall, United Kingdom
* &quot;Atlantic&quot;, a song by the American rock band [[Thrice]] on the album ''Vheissu''
* ''[[The Atlantic]]'', an American magazine founded as ''The Atlantic Monthly'' in 1857
* [[The Atlantics]], an Australian surf rock band formed in the early 1960s
* [[Atlantic (Theatre album)|''Atlantic'' (Theatre album)]], an album by the band [[Theatre]]

==Other uses==
* [[Atlantic (period)]] of palaeoclimatology
* [[Atlantic (supermarkets)]], a supermarket chain in Greece
* [[Atlantic languages]] (formerly West Atlantic), a language family in West Africa
* [[Atlantic Championship]], developmental open-wheel racing series in North America
* [[Atlantic Philanthropies]], a private foundation
* [[Atlantic League of Professional Baseball]], an American professional baseball league 
* [[The Atlantic (Atlanta)]], an Atlanta skyscraper
* [[Atlantic (Los Angeles Metro station)]], a Metro Gold Line light rail station
* [[Atlantic (company)]], Italian toy manufacturer

==See also==
* [[Atlantik (disambiguation)]]

== recovered place names ==
* [[Atlantic, Gulf and Pacific Steamship Company]], of Baltimore, Maryland was incorporated in May 1920
* [[Atlantic, Massachusetts]]
* [[Atlantic, Suwannee River and Gulf Railway]], incorporated under the general incorporation laws of Florida
* [[Atlantic, Seattle]], the northernmost neighborhood of the Rainier Valley, USA, between Mount Baker Ridge and Beacon Hill
* [[Atlantic, Greenville and Western Railway]], a railroad company chartered by the South Carolina General Assembly in 1885
* [[Atlantic, Waycross and Northern Railroad]], formed in 1911 as a successor to the St
* [[Atlantic, Gulf and West India Transit]]
* [[Atlantic, Valdosta and Western Railway]], operated from Valdosta, Georgia, to Jacksonville, Florida, and was nicknamed the ''Jacksonville Short Line''. In 1902, it was purchased by the Georgia Southern and Florida Railway
* [[Atlantic, Mississippi and Ohio Railroad]], formed in 1870 in Virginia from 3 east-west railroads which traversed across the southern portion of the state

== recovered names (non-redirect) ==
* [[Atlantic Yards]], a mixed-use commercial and residential development project of 16 high-rise buildings, currently proposed in the neighborhood of Prospect Heights, adjacent to Downtown Brooklyn and Fort Greene in Brooklyn, New York City
* [[Atlantic Superstore]], a Canadian supermarket chain of 54 stores in the Maritime provinces of Nova Scotia, New Brunswick, and Prince Edward Island
* [[Marine Atlantic]], an independent Canadian Crown corporation offering ferry services between the provinces of Newfoundland and Labrador and Nova Scotia
* [[Atlantic Aircraft]], was a US subsidiary of the Dutch Fokker Company, responsible for sales and information about Fokker imports, and eventually constructing various Fokker designs
* [[Operation Atlantic]], Atlantic Wall&amp;#160;– Bodyguard&amp;#160;– Fortitude&amp;#160;– Zeppelin&amp;#160;– Combined Bomber Offensive&amp;#160;– Pointblank&amp;#160;– Postage Able&amp;#160;– Tarbrush&amp;#160;– Tiger
* [[Atlantic Schooners]], a conditional Canadian Football League expansion team that was to begin play in 1984 out of Halifax, Nova Scotia
* [[Atlantic Star]], a campaign medal of the British Commonwealth, awarded for service in World War II
* [[Atlantic Center Plaza]], a 24-floor office highrise located at 1180 West Peachtree Street in Atlanta Georgia, across the street from the One Atlantic Center. The plaza was completed in 2001.[''citation needed'']
* [[Atlantic Broadband]], a privately held cable company with headquarters in Quincy, Massachusetts
* [[Air Atlantic]], a Canadian airline, operating a fleet of BAe 146-200 and Dash 8-100 aircraft
* [[Atlantic University]], an institution of higher education in Virginia Beach, Virginia. It is associated with the Edgar Cayce organization, the Association for Research and Enlightenment (ARE), and its offices are in the ARE headquarters
* [[Atlantic Station]], a large brownfield redevelopment project at the northwestern edge of Midtown Atlanta, Georgia
* [[Atlantic Open]], a golf tournament on the European Tour in 1990. It was held at Estela Golf Club in Oporto, Portugal
* [[Atlantic Sampler]], a promotional single by the band King Crimson, released in 1973. Its tracks are from the album ''Larks' Tongues in Aspic'' (1973)
* [[Sky Atlantic]], a television channel owned by British Sky Broadcasting, which launched on 1 February 2011 on Sky in the United Kingdom and the Republic of Ireland
* [[Atlantic Forest]], a region of tropical and subtropical moist forest, tropical dry forest, tropical savanna, semi deciduous forest and mangrove forests which extends along the Atlantic coast of Brazil from Rio Grande do Norte state in the north to Rio Grande do Sul state in the south, and inland as far as Paraguay and the Misiones Province of Argentina
* [[Formula Atlantic]], a specification of open wheel racing car developed in the 1970s. It is currently used in professional racing through the IMSA Atlantic Championship and amateur racing through Sports Car Club of America Formula Atlantic
* [[Atlantic Bamboo Rat]], a spiny rat species from South America. It is found in Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay. It is the only member of the genus ''&lt;b&gt;Kannabateomys&lt;/b&gt;''
* [[Atlantic Charter]], a pivotal policy statement first issued in August 1941 that early in World War II defined the Allied goals for the post-war world
* [[Atlantic Terminal Mall]], a shopping mall located on Atlantic Avenue surrounded by Hanson Place, Fort Greene Place and Flatbush Avenue in the Fort Greene section of Brooklyn, New York
* [[Halifax Atlantic]], a provincial electoral district in Nova Scotia, Canada, that elects one member of the Nova Scotia House of Assembly
* [[Atlantic City Railroad]], a Philadelphia and Reading Railway subsidiary that became part of Pennsylvania-Reading Seashore Lines in 1933
* [[Touchdown Atlantic]], a series of Canadian Football League games played in the maritime provinces
* [[Atlantic Bronze Age]], a cultural complex of the period of approximately 1300–700&amp;#160;BC that includes different cultures in Portugal, Andalusia, Galicia and the British Isles
* [[Atlantic Bridge]], a flight route from Gander, Newfoundland, Canada to Scotland, with a refueling stop in Iceland

